SIMPLE: scythe
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scythe
<hw>Scythe</hw> <pr>(s⟦imac⟧th)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>sithe</ets>, AS. s⟦imac⟧⟦edh⟧e, <ets>sig⟦edh⟧e</ets>; akin to Icel.
<ets>sig⟦edh⟧r</ets> a sickle, LG. <ets>segd</ets>, <ets>seged</ets>,
<ets>seed</ets>, <ets>seid</ets>, OHG. <ets>segansa</ets> sickle,
scythe, G. <ets>sense</ets> scythe, and to E. <ets>saw</ets> a cutting
instrument. See <er>Saw</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>sithe</asp> and <asp>sythe</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An
instrument for mowing grass, grain, or the like, by hand, composed of a
long, curving blade, with a sharp edge, made fast to a long handle,
called a <xex>snath</xex>, which is bent into a form convenient for
use.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sharp-edged <qex>scythe</qex> shears up the spiring grass.</q>
<rj><qau>Drayton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whatever thing⟦br⟧
The <qex>scythe</qex> of Time mows down.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Antiq.)</fld> <def>A scythe-shaped blade attached
to ancient war chariots.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1296 pr=PCP --></p>

<p><ent>Scythe</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scythe
<hw>Scythe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cut with a
scythe; to cut off as with a scythe; to mow.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Time had not <qex>scythed</qex> all that youth begun.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scythed</ent>⟦br⟧
